      <zones>
        <zone h='100000' id='2' type-v2='layout-basic' w='100000' x='0' y='0'>
          <zone h='98118' id='1' param='vert' removable='false' type-v2='layout-flow' w='98546' x='727' y='941'>
            <zone h='4000' id='3' type-v2='title' w='98546' x='727' y='941' />
            <zone h='11882' id='4' is-fixed='true' paired-zone-id='5' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard-nav' w='98546' x='727' y='4941' />
            <zone h='82236' id='5' paired-zone-id='4' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard' w='98546' x='727' y='16823'>
              <flipboard active-id='8' nav-type='caption' show-nav-arrows='true'>
                <story-points>
                  <story-point caption='Career Choices: Are Workers Skipping Degree-Heavy Roles?' captured-sheet='occ 3' id='1' />
                  <story-point caption='AI and the Job Market: Are Degrees Still Driving Demand?' captured-sheet='occ 4' id='2' />
                  <story-point caption='AI-Era Workforce: Are Gender Gaps Widening or Shrinking?' captured-sheet='occ 5' id='3' />
                  <story-point caption='Degrees vs. Demographics: Career Preferences Across Ages' captured-sheet='occ 6' id='4' />
                  <story-point caption='Where Are the Degree Jobs Going? Regional Patterns of High-Skill Employment' captured-sheet='occ 7' id='5'>
                    <capturedDeltas>
                      <worksheet name='occ 7'>
                        <style delta-type='added'>
                          <style-rule element='axis'>
                            <encoding attr='space' class='0' field='[federated.0pb4zrw06twjm215avjks0uzcvpk].[Latitude (generated)]' field-type='quantitative' projection='EPSG:3857' scope='rows' type='space' />
                            <encoding attr='space' class='0' field='[federated.0pb4zrw06twjm215avjks0uzcvpk].[Longitude (generated)]' field-type='quantitative' projection='EPSG:3857' scope='cols' type='space' />
                          </style-rule>
                        </style>
                      </worksheet>
                    </capturedDeltas>
                  </story-point>
                  <story-point caption='What Does the Workforce Look Like? A Snapshot by Age and Occupation' captured-sheet='occ 8' id='6' />
                  <story-point caption='AI Impact: Workforce Contraction and Expansion by Region' captured-sheet='occ 11' id='7' />
                  <story-point caption='Comparing Regional Employment Share' captured-sheet='occ Dashboard 1' id='8' />
                </story-points>
              </flipboard>
            </zone>
          </zone>
          <zone-style>
            <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
            <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
            <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
            <format attr='margin' value='8' />
          </zone-style>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='17427' hidden='true' id='6' story-point-id='1' type-v2='text' w='33268' x='11614' y='19710'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Younger cohorts (16–24) show lower participation in degree-oriented occupations like professional and managerial roles, while mid-career groups (35–49) dominate these sectors, hinting at potential educational or entry barriers.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='26471' hidden='true' id='7' story-point-id='2' type-v2='text' w='30818' x='68636' y='30824'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Between 2011 and 2021, employment in professional and managerial roles declined, while non-degree sectors like administrative and trades saw gains, suggesting a shift in labor demand away from traditional graduate pipelines.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='20941' hidden='true' id='8' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='31909' x='65818' y='36941'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Despite tech-driven transformation, strong gender skews persist. Females dominate caring and admin roles, while males overwhelmingly occupy technical and skilled trades — many of which are less degree-reliant.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='39176' hidden='true' id='9' story-point-id='4' type-v2='text' w='15727' x='84000' y='29882'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Age influences occupational patterns — younger groups cluster in customer service and elementary roles, while older groups shift toward managerial and professional fields, reflecting career maturity and possible qualification access.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='14118' hidden='true' id='10' story-point-id='5' type-v2='text' w='33273' x='2182' y='19765'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Degree-heavy occupations remain concentrated in urban and economically developed regions, emphasizing the geographic divide in access to higher-skill, higher-qualification employment. </run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='7294' hidden='true' id='11' story-point-id='6' type-v2='text' w='81818' x='1636' y='84588'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>Professional and associate technical roles form the largest workforce segments, but significant shares persist in manual, trade, and customer-facing occupations — not all requiring degrees. </run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='36000' hidden='true' id='12' story-point-id='7' type-v2='text' w='14818' x='84727' y='28824'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#000000' fontsize='10'>While some regions expanded employment dramatically post-2011, others saw double-digit losses. AI-driven shifts may be amplifying regional inequalities in job opportunity and industry relevance.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' h='20824' id='13' story-point-id='8' type-v2='text' w='14636' x='30636' y='18941'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#ffffff' fontsize='8'>In 2011, employment was concentrated in traditional industrial and administrative hubs, with limited dispersion into peripheral regions. Urban centers dominated the distribution of high-skill jobs</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='20471' id='14' story-point-id='8' type-v2='text' w='16455' x='73727' y='19059'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontalignment='0' fontcolor='#ffffff' fontsize='8'>By 2021, high-skill employment had become more geographically distributed, indicating a shift toward digital, remote, and service-driven roles that are less centralized and potentially less degree-dependent.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <simple-id uuid='{CC641371-F63D-444A-9D85-4D9D73818F15}' />
    </dashboard>
  </dashboards>
